WEBVTT

00:43.002 --> 00:45.046
[HORSE NEIGHS]

02:06.836 --> 02:07.879
[HONKS HORN THEN SIGHS]

02:08.045 --> 02:10.006
We made it.

02:12.342 --> 02:15.011
[SEBASTIAN SNORES
THEN POPCORN BARKS]

02:15.929 --> 02:18.431
[SEBASTIAN YELPS THEN BARKS]

02:18.640 --> 02:21.476
CHELSEA: I gotta go, I gotta go.
-Last one out's a rotten cheese.

02:21.684 --> 02:22.727
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

02:22.894 --> 02:23.937
[BREATHES DEEPLY]

02:24.103 --> 02:27.690
Just breathe that air. Very Alpsy.

02:27.899 --> 02:31.611
Look, look, horses. Let's go riding.

02:31.820 --> 02:34.989
- Can we please? Can we?
-Chelsea, chill.

02:35.198 --> 02:38.493
-We've got all month to ride the horses.
SKIPPER: Whoa.

02:38.701 --> 02:42.539
BARBIE:
I know, it's the Matterhorn. Isn't it amazing?

02:42.747 --> 02:44.791
No, I mean this LCD screen.

02:44.999 --> 02:49.420
Thirty-three megapixel resolution
with 24.7 million colours.

02:49.629 --> 02:53.341
- It's like we're there.
-Ha-ha. Skipper, we are there.

02:54.551 --> 02:59.097
Oh, yeah, nice mountains.
But on this baby, I can zoom in.

02:59.305 --> 03:01.391
MARLENE: Barbie.
-Aunt Marlene.

03:01.599 --> 03:04.394
MARLENE:
Skipper. Stacie.

03:04.602 --> 03:06.104
Chelsea.

03:06.312 --> 03:08.857
Welcome to the Alpine Riding Academy.

03:09.065 --> 03:11.109
BARBIE: Thank you so much
for having us here.

03:11.276 --> 03:12.610
[GIRLS CHATTERING]

03:12.777 --> 03:15.029
-Hello, Barbie.
-Hello, Max.

03:15.238 --> 03:17.115
MARIE: Barbie.
-Whoa!

03:17.323 --> 03:19.242
-Oh, Marie.
-Hi, Marie.

03:19.450 --> 03:23.288
- You're really here.
-Please excuse my sister.

03:23.496 --> 03:27.208
-She was raised by squirrels.
MARLENE: I'm so glad you're all here.

03:27.876 --> 03:29.335
Please, come inside.

03:29.544 --> 03:33.423
Barbie, I love the hand-tooled
detail on your luggage.

03:33.631 --> 03:35.717
- It's awfully smart.
BARBIE: Thanks.

03:35.925 --> 03:40.805
I got a suitcase just like it.
Except mine is covered with scorpions.

03:43.725 --> 03:45.852
[SUITCASE THUDDING]

03:46.060 --> 03:48.354
[DOORKNOB RATTLING AND
KIDS GRUNTING & CHATTERING]

03:50.023 --> 03:51.357
-Ooh.
-Whoa.

03:52.066 --> 03:53.985
This is it.

03:54.193 --> 03:56.654
The flowers were my little touch.

03:56.863 --> 04:01.492
-And I picked off most of the bugs.
-Most of the bugs?

04:01.701 --> 04:06.539
Oh, and I put sweets on all
of your pillows just like in a hotel.

04:06.748 --> 04:10.376
Oh. Of course, that was three days ago
and some of them melted...

04:10.543 --> 04:11.920
...and Popcorn ate the rest...

04:12.086 --> 04:14.672
...but you can still smell them when you sleep.

04:16.132 --> 04:18.468
MARLENE: Thank you, children.
MARIE: Popcorn.

04:18.676 --> 04:21.012
MARLENE:
Now back to your chores.

04:21.220 --> 04:24.307
-I got dibs on the top bunk.
-No, me.

04:24.515 --> 04:26.684
BOTH:
One, two, three, shoot.

04:26.893 --> 04:29.395
-Yes.
-No.

04:29.604 --> 04:31.022
[HORSE NEIGHS]

04:31.606 --> 04:35.526
The room's perfect, Aunt Marlene,
and I can't wait to find my horse.

04:35.735 --> 04:37.403
CHELSEA:
Your champion horse.

04:37.612 --> 04:40.573
Barbie's gonna win
the Pacific Steeplechase with it.

04:40.782 --> 04:44.744
- Well, I don't know about that. Heh.
SKIPPER: Of course you'll win.

04:44.953 --> 04:47.038
You're only the best rider on the West Coast.

04:47.205 --> 04:51.000
Thanks, but that depends a lot
on finding just the right horse.

04:51.793 --> 04:55.296
The horse of your dreams, hmm?
Every rider has one.

04:55.505 --> 04:57.006
Something like that.

04:57.215 --> 05:01.928
Well, I believe we raise the finest jumping horses
in all of Switzerland.

05:02.136 --> 05:04.764
I'm certain you'll find one here
that's to your liking.

05:04.973 --> 05:08.101
Have you got one that looks like this?

05:08.309 --> 05:12.230
- My. That's quite a horse.
-Isn't it?

05:12.855 --> 05:16.067
-I hope I brought enough glitter.
-When can we get started?

05:16.275 --> 05:18.361
MARLENE: How about now?
STACIE: Yay!

05:18.528 --> 05:20.154
CHELSEA: Whoo-hoo!
-Let's go.

05:21.197 --> 05:23.783
Skipper? Don't you want to see the horses too?

05:23.992 --> 05:26.828
You guys go ahead. I need to update my blog.

05:27.036 --> 05:28.538
You used to love horses.

05:28.705 --> 05:31.082
When you were younger,
we couldn't get you off them.

05:31.290 --> 05:32.917
Well, I guess people change...

05:33.126 --> 05:35.962
...and right now, all my peeps are at TechCon...

05:36.170 --> 05:37.755
...trying out the latest gear...

05:37.922 --> 05:40.800
...while I'm stuck here listening to cows yodel.

05:41.134 --> 05:43.553
[cow MOOS]

05:48.975 --> 05:51.602
So first time on a horse, is it?

05:51.811 --> 05:52.979
Yeah, it's my first...

05:53.187 --> 05:56.441
...but it won't take me long to ace it
like I do every sport.

05:56.649 --> 05:59.902
Still, you might want to go slowly at first.

06:00.069 --> 06:02.321
Thanks, but not too slow.

06:02.530 --> 06:04.532
Did I mention I'm kind of a natural jock?

06:04.741 --> 06:05.783
Yes.

06:06.367 --> 06:08.327
We caught it the first time.

06:08.536 --> 06:11.497
We'll match Chelsea and Stacie
with their horses first.

06:12.582 --> 06:16.669
Girls, meet your teachers.

06:16.836 --> 06:21.299
Ooh. I want that one or that one.
Can I have two?

06:21.507 --> 06:23.176
Can we pick whichever horse we want'?

06:23.384 --> 06:24.844
MARLENE:
No, no, chÃ©rie.

06:25.053 --> 06:27.680
The beginning riders never pick their horses.

06:27.847 --> 06:30.933
CHELSEA: Huh?
-The horses pick you.

06:31.142 --> 06:33.394
-Excuse me?
MAX: You'll see.

06:34.020 --> 06:38.900
Step into the corral and then stand really still.

06:53.998 --> 06:55.166
[NEIGHS]

06:55.374 --> 06:57.376
[HORSE SNIFFS]

06:57.543 --> 07:00.630
- Aww. . . .
-it's okay, Chels.

07:06.344 --> 07:07.887
[GRUNTS SOFTLY]

07:08.054 --> 07:10.098
[GIGGLES]

07:10.556 --> 07:12.767
Looks like you've got a new bestie, Stace.

07:12.975 --> 07:17.605
STACIE: What's her name?
-Stacie, meet Pepper.

07:17.814 --> 07:19.273
Nice to meet you, Pepper.

07:19.440 --> 07:20.775
[SNORTS]

07:20.983 --> 07:22.985
[HORSE APPROACHING]

07:29.075 --> 07:30.660
[NEIGHS]

07:35.373 --> 07:37.166
[SIGHS]

07:37.333 --> 07:39.001
[HORSE SNIFFING]

07:41.129 --> 07:42.797
[SNORTS]

07:44.549 --> 07:45.591
[WHINNIES]

07:45.758 --> 07:48.511
MARLENE: It looks like you too
have been chosen, Chelsea.

07:48.719 --> 07:50.054
Meet Dash.

07:50.221 --> 07:52.056
[NEIGHS]

07:56.352 --> 07:59.981
-Where's the rest of her?
MARLENE: I'm afraid that's all there is.

08:00.189 --> 08:03.818
But Dash is a very sweet pony,
and she seems to really like you.

08:04.026 --> 08:06.487
But she's so little.

08:07.071 --> 08:10.158
Why can't I have a big horse like Stacie's?

08:10.366 --> 08:11.868
Chelsea, give Dash a chance.

08:12.076 --> 08:16.747
There'll be plenty of time for big horses
when you're a little bigger.

08:16.956 --> 08:20.751
ETIENNE:
Catastrophe. Disaster. Calamity.

08:20.960 --> 08:22.962
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

08:23.129 --> 08:26.883
Madame Marlene, we are ruined.

08:27.091 --> 08:29.135
What is it this time, Etienne?

08:29.343 --> 08:31.262
Look at these fly bonnets.

08:32.138 --> 08:33.890
Just look at them.

08:34.682 --> 08:36.017
-So?
-So...

08:36.225 --> 08:39.520
...I ordered them in aubergine
to match the halters.

08:39.729 --> 08:44.442
But look. Look.
Would you call that aubergine?

08:44.650 --> 08:45.985
-Hmm?
-Uh....

08:46.152 --> 08:47.945
-No?
MAX: He has a point.

08:48.154 --> 08:50.156
That is so not aubergine.

08:50.364 --> 08:53.743
You see? The child is clearly offended.

08:53.951 --> 08:58.664
How are we supposed to win a tournament
with clashing fly bonnets?

08:58.873 --> 09:02.835
-Even the flies will be laughing at us.
STACIE: Tournament?

09:03.002 --> 09:04.212
I like the sound of that.

09:04.420 --> 09:06.505
The annual tournament between our academy...

09:06.714 --> 09:10.384
...and all the other local riding schools,
and the prize money is substantial.

09:10.593 --> 09:11.928
This year we're hosting.

09:12.094 --> 09:16.307
Hmp! But not if our horses are too embarrassed
to take the field.

09:16.515 --> 09:18.226
I'd better take care of this.

09:18.434 --> 09:22.146
Max, Marie,
you get Stacie and Chelsea started.

09:22.355 --> 09:25.358
Barbie, you of course
may choose your own horse.

09:25.566 --> 09:27.526
Look over the thoroughbreds in the stable.

09:28.110 --> 09:30.821
Every one's a prize jumper.

09:31.030 --> 09:32.240
Did you see the stitching?

09:32.406 --> 09:35.534
I specifically asked for a cross-hatch stitch.

09:35.743 --> 09:37.787
This is not a cross or even a hatch.

09:37.995 --> 09:39.872
And did you see the halters they sent?

09:40.081 --> 09:41.499
Who was that?

09:41.707 --> 09:45.169
That was Monsieur Etienne, our riding master.

09:45.336 --> 09:48.506
ls he always like that?
Like he just bit into a lemon.

09:48.714 --> 09:51.842
Pretty much. He's a good teacher though.

09:52.051 --> 09:53.386
[CHUCKLES]

09:53.594 --> 09:55.429
Go.

09:55.596 --> 09:58.683
Come on, girl. Good girl.

09:58.891 --> 10:01.477
-She's all yours.
-Hmph.

10:02.144 --> 10:04.438
Okay. So how do I get on this thing?

10:04.647 --> 10:06.649
Oh, yes, well, before we begin...

10:06.857 --> 10:10.528
...I thought it might be instructive
to review the history of the English...

10:10.736 --> 10:12.738
...or eventing saddle.

10:12.947 --> 10:14.573
ls that necessary--?

10:14.782 --> 10:17.910
Here you'll see the gullet, the cantle,
the girth buckle--

10:18.119 --> 10:20.204
What my brother is trying to say is...

10:20.371 --> 10:23.207
...stick your foot in here
and throw your leg over the horse.

10:23.374 --> 10:25.876
-That's the big thing right there.
STACIE: Got it.

10:26.043 --> 10:28.337
-Thanks.
MAX: Right, of course.

10:28.504 --> 10:30.339
Who needs 400 years of tradition?

10:30.548 --> 10:34.135
Fine, just jump on and kick her into drive.

10:36.846 --> 10:38.139
SKIPPER:
Wait.

10:38.347 --> 10:41.267
First time on a horse? Definitely video-worthy.

10:41.475 --> 10:46.397
Look at that style, that conï¬dent approach.

10:46.605 --> 10:48.733
As the future champion approaches...

10:48.941 --> 10:51.944
...the animal humbly yields to its new master.

10:52.111 --> 10:53.279
[NEIGHS]

10:53.446 --> 10:54.739
Whoa! Uhn!

10:54.905 --> 10:56.115
[BOYS LAUGHING]

10:58.617 --> 11:00.870
Look. Alpine has a new trick rider.

11:01.037 --> 11:02.955
What do you call that move?

11:03.164 --> 11:04.457
The mud dive?

11:04.623 --> 11:06.751
[BOYS LAUGHING]

11:06.917 --> 11:08.794
Whoa!

11:08.961 --> 11:12.131
[BOYS LAUGHING]

11:12.298 --> 11:17.887
Hey, Marie, if that's your best rider,
our winning streak seems pretty safe.

11:18.095 --> 11:19.764
[BOYS LAUGHING]

11:19.930 --> 11:21.182
Oh, yes.

11:22.933 --> 11:28.230
Hey, if you're looking up world's greatest rider,
I'm right here.

11:28.439 --> 11:32.777
Actually, I was just looking up doofus.
See? Right here.

11:32.943 --> 11:34.278
[MONKEY GIBBERING]

11:34.445 --> 11:35.488
[BOYS LAUGHING]

11:35.654 --> 11:37.281
She got you good, Jonas.

11:37.490 --> 11:39.700
-How droll.
JONAS: Ahem.

11:40.201 --> 11:42.203
[LAUGHING]

11:43.162 --> 11:44.705
MAX: Don't mind them.
-Pbbt!

11:44.914 --> 11:48.125
They're from Ecole Montagne,
the riding school just down the road.

11:48.292 --> 11:51.629
They're just trying to get under our skin
with the tournament coming up.

11:51.796 --> 11:55.257
Of course, it doesn't really matter.
We always lose anyway.

11:55.466 --> 11:56.759
Usually to them.

11:56.967 --> 11:59.136
MAX:
You never know. This year could be different.

11:59.345 --> 12:05.851
Statistically speaking,
we're bound to win within, hmm, 63 years.

12:06.060 --> 12:09.605
Now that I'm on the team,
we'll cream those creeps.

12:09.772 --> 12:11.565
Whoa! Uhn!

12:11.732 --> 12:13.484
SKIPPER:
Heh. Yep.

12:13.651 --> 12:15.778
- Classic.
MAX & MARIE: Ha-ha-ha.

12:19.698 --> 12:21.951
[HORSES WHINNYING]

12:36.215 --> 12:37.258
[SNORTS]

12:42.471 --> 12:43.889
[NEIGHS]

12:44.723 --> 12:45.766
[SNIFFS]

12:45.933 --> 12:46.976
[CHUCKLES]

12:47.143 --> 12:48.394
[GRUNTS]

12:53.190 --> 12:54.567
[SNORTS]

12:56.986 --> 12:58.529
[HORSE NEIGHS]

13:04.452 --> 13:06.620
[BARKING]

13:07.663 --> 13:10.666
Why, hello, Sebastian.

13:11.208 --> 13:15.421
Hello, Popcorn. Now run along.

13:15.629 --> 13:18.215
Sorry, that took so long, Barbie dear.

13:18.841 --> 13:23.220
Monsieur Etienne can be a bit temperamental
at times.

13:23.429 --> 13:25.639
-lnoï¬ced.
-He's worth it.

13:25.848 --> 13:29.477
We're hoping he can lead us
to our first tournament win in 11 years.

13:29.685 --> 13:32.605
I'm sure you've got lots of good riders.

13:32.771 --> 13:34.356
We did once...

13:34.565 --> 13:39.403
...but frankly, enrolment has been incredibly low
these last few years.

13:39.695 --> 13:42.656
So have you found your horse yet?

13:42.865 --> 13:45.951
Everyone in this group is from champion stock.

13:46.160 --> 13:49.788
I'm just not sure.

13:51.499 --> 13:53.542
This one seems nice.

13:53.709 --> 13:56.837
Ah. Finian. Excellent choice.

13:57.046 --> 14:01.634
His sire was the winner of the Virginia Gold Cup,
so he'll be right at home in America.

14:01.842 --> 14:04.136
You two would make an excellent team.

14:05.346 --> 14:07.389
BARBIE:
Hmm. Maybe.

14:10.434 --> 14:12.853
[ROOSTER CROWS]

14:25.366 --> 14:29.161
[GRUNTING]

14:31.664 --> 14:34.333
[YAWNS]

14:35.543 --> 14:37.461
[BLEATS AND BARBIE SCREAMS]

14:37.628 --> 14:39.588
[BOTH TALKING INDISTINCTLY]

14:40.798 --> 14:43.676
Oh, no, you don't, you grabby goat.

14:43.884 --> 14:45.886
[ALL YELLING]

14:49.598 --> 14:50.891
Wa key, wa key.

14:51.100 --> 14:52.518
Oh, hi, Barnaby.

14:52.726 --> 14:53.769
You know him?

14:53.978 --> 14:57.273
-He's eating my blanket.
-Yes, he likes wool.

14:57.481 --> 14:59.358
Last week, he ate all my socks.

14:59.567 --> 15:02.778
It's a miracle he's still alive.

15:02.945 --> 15:04.446
Get him!

15:05.030 --> 15:06.365
[ALL SCREAM THEN GRUNT]

15:07.825 --> 15:12.246
Breakfast in 20 minutes.
Hope you like Kartoffelkuchen.

15:12.454 --> 15:13.956
[BARNABY BLEATING]

15:20.963 --> 15:25.426
No, no, no, mademoiselle.

15:25.634 --> 15:30.514
We swoop with the curry comb, huh?
Not attack. Huh?

15:30.723 --> 15:33.225
Long curving motions.

15:33.392 --> 15:34.602
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

15:34.768 --> 15:37.605
And swoop, ah, oui.

15:37.771 --> 15:39.356
And swoop. Yes?

15:39.565 --> 15:43.068
Bend the knees and swoop. Ah.

15:43.277 --> 15:45.404
Got it, swoop, swoop.

15:45.613 --> 15:47.781
Bend.Hey.

15:48.824 --> 15:51.785
Give me a break. I'm new at swooping.

15:51.994 --> 15:55.831
Perfect. Dash, you're going to be so pretty.

15:56.040 --> 15:58.459
Don't you think so, Chelse?

15:59.752 --> 16:00.794
[DASH SNORTS]

16:00.961 --> 16:02.504
Oof!

16:03.380 --> 16:04.673
[DASH NEIGHS]

16:04.840 --> 16:07.092
-Oh....
-I can't wait to get out...

16:07.259 --> 16:09.803
...and feel the wind in my hair.

16:11.680 --> 16:12.723
[SIGHS]

16:12.890 --> 16:14.975
Yippee-ki-yay.

16:21.899 --> 16:24.693
Ow. O-W.

16:26.362 --> 16:27.738
BARBIE:
Hyah.

16:30.532 --> 16:35.037
Uh-uh. Reign back, Mademoiselle Barbie.
No faster than a walk, please.

16:35.245 --> 16:40.751
We must make certain everyone is riding
at the same pace, n'est-ce pas?

16:40.918 --> 16:42.002
[SIGHS]

16:47.257 --> 16:48.300
Whoa.

16:48.467 --> 16:49.843
[NEIGHS]

16:59.853 --> 17:02.564
Skipper, Stacey, did you see that?

17:02.773 --> 17:05.233
-See what?
-That horse.

17:06.484 --> 17:08.319
What are you talking about?

17:08.987 --> 17:12.616
I guess, nothing.

17:13.951 --> 17:15.953
Nothing at all.

17:18.705 --> 17:20.708
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

17:24.211 --> 17:26.338
Now, tell me the truth, Barnaby.

17:26.547 --> 17:28.674
Doesn't clover taste better than wool?

17:29.049 --> 17:30.592
[BLEATING]

17:30.801 --> 17:33.345
Ha-ha. I'm glad you agree.

17:33.512 --> 17:37.349
[DOGS BARKING AND SNARLING]

17:38.892 --> 17:40.978
BARBIE:
That's the horse.

17:42.730 --> 17:47.568
